# PipeGuard pipeline-repair remediation corpus (curated; ADR-0009). origin: contrived.
# One JSON object per line (RemediationEntry). ADVISORY only: every entry proposes a
# HUMAN-REVIEWED pipeline guard, never an auto-applied fix and never a verdict. Conservative /
# hedged language; NO threshold value is invented — templates defer to "the runbook's configured
# gate/band" (docs/data/qc_metrics.md owns the numbers). Grounded in ADR-0008's issue taxonomy +
# the runbook. `attach_to` is a PipelineStage (or null for a workflow-wide guard); `scope` is a
# Gate phase. Blank and '#' lines are ignored by the loader.
{"id": "repair_barcode_index_swap", "category": "provenance", "rule_ids": ["PROV-001"], "title": "Barcode / index mismatch vs sample sheet", "keywords": ["barcode", "index", "index2", "i7", "i5", "sample", "sheet", "samplesheet", "demultiplex", "demux", "mismatch", "collision", "swap", "hopping", "provenance", "custody"], "summary": "Add an index-distance guard to the demultiplexing step: require a minimum Hamming distance between assigned i7/i5 index pairs and fail closed on index collisions (rather than assigning ambiguous reads), and reconcile the sample sheet against the LIMS index manifest before demux runs. On patterned flow cells, consider unique dual indexing to bound index hopping.", "attach_to": "demux", "scope": "preflight", "rationale": "A declared-vs-observed index mismatch most often traces to a sample-sheet data-entry error, an index swap during library prep/pooling, or index hopping; guarding the demux inputs and failing closed keeps chain of custody from being silently assumed. This is a proposed, human-reviewed guard, not an auto-applied change.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 1 — barcode/index integrity (ESCALATE); ADR-0008 issue taxonomy", "tags": ["preflight", "provenance", "demux"]}
{"id": "repair_sample_absent_from_sheet", "category": "provenance", "rule_ids": ["PROV-002"], "title": "Sample has QC output but no sample-sheet row", "keywords": ["sample", "absent", "missing", "samplesheet", "sheet", "orphan", "unregistered", "output", "demultiplex", "demux", "provenance", "custody"], "summary": "Add a demux-completeness check that asserts every produced per-sample output maps back to exactly one sample-sheet row, and fail closed on an orphan output instead of emitting it. Surface the reconciliation (sheet vs pooling vs LIMS) as a required pre-release step so an unregistered sample cannot flow downstream.", "attach_to": "demux", "scope": "preflight", "rationale": "A sample with QC output but no sheet row usually reflects a demux/sample-sheet mismatch, a late-added or renamed library, or an accidental extra output — its provenance cannot be established from the sheet alone, so the guard holds it for tracing rather than releasing it.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 1 — barcode/index integrity; schemas.md provenance invariants", "tags": ["preflight", "provenance", "demux"]}
{"id": "repair_missing_intake_metadata", "category": "metadata", "rule_ids": ["META-001", "META-002"], "title": "Missing required intake metadata", "keywords": ["metadata", "intake", "missing", "subject", "tissue", "library", "prep", "submitter", "accessioning", "lims", "traceability", "provenance", "field"], "summary": "Add a required-field gate at intake/accessioning that blocks a run from entering the pipeline until the runbook's required intake fields (subject, tissue, library prep, submitter) are present and non-empty in the LIMS record. Prefer holding at intake over failing mid-run, and let the operator complete the record and resume.", "attach_to": "intake", "scope": "preflight", "rationale": "Missing intake metadata reflects an incomplete accessioning/LIMS handoff rather than a sequencing defect; catching it at intake restores downstream traceability without discarding otherwise-good reads. The required-field list is read from the runbook, not hard-coded.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 1 — intake; runbook require_metadata_fields; schemas.md Sample metadata", "tags": ["preflight", "metadata", "intake"]}
{"id": "repair_pipeline_step_failure", "category": "pipeline", "rule_ids": ["PIPE-001"], "title": "Logged pipeline step failure", "keywords": ["pipeline", "failed", "failure", "error", "exit", "code", "crash", "segmentation", "fault", "step", "process", "nextflow", "operational", "infrastructure", "filesystem", "network", "retry", "rerun"], "summary": "Add a bounded retry-with-backoff and an explicit resource (memory/time) guard to the failing workflow process, plus a pre-flight input-integrity check, so a transient infrastructure failure requeues automatically instead of surfacing as a per-sample failure. Alert only after the retry budget is exhausted. This guard is workflow-wide (no single stage) and needs approver sign-off before it is wired.", "attach_to": null, "scope": "preflight", "rationale": "A logged nonzero exit / crash / segfault is usually operational (a transient network or filesystem race, resource exhaustion, or a tool crash) rather than a data-quality defect, so the runbook favors a bounded rerun once the cause is cleared; the guard automates that safely without touching data. Because the failing step is not known a priori, the fix attaches at the workflow level, not one stage.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Verdict policy 3 (operational/filesystem failures -> RERUN); runbook log_failure_markers", "tags": ["preflight", "pipeline", "operational"]}
{"id": "repair_low_q30", "category": "qc", "rule_ids": ["QC-Q30"], "title": "Q30 below the platform expectation", "keywords": ["q30", "quality", "phred", "basecall", "read", "length", "sequencing", "overclustering", "reagent", "flowcell", "gate", "low", "below"], "summary": "Keep the Q30 gate at read-QC comparing against the runbook's configured Q30 threshold for this read length, and route Q30-failing lanes to the sequencing team for a resequencing decision rather than passing them silently. Do not lower the gate to force a pass; surface whether neighboring lanes are also low (a run-level signal).", "attach_to": "read_qc", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "Low Q30 is usually a run/lane-level sequencing-quality signal (overclustering, reagent/flow-cell degradation, late-cycle drop-off, or a read length beyond the kit's rated spec), so the remediation is to gate and escalate for a wet-lab decision, not to alter the pipeline's data. The threshold comes from the runbook, never invented here.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 2 Q30 + platform matrix (RUO spec, not a clinical gate); runbook qc_thresholds", "tags": ["qc", "read_qc"]}
{"id": "repair_low_coverage", "category": "coverage", "rule_ids": ["QC-MEAN_COVERAGE"], "title": "Low mean/median coverage depth", "keywords": ["coverage", "depth", "mean", "median", "low", "shallow", "target", "panel", "bed", "yield", "undersequenced", "modality", "mosdepth"], "summary": "At the coverage stage, verify the target BED/panel and the assay's configured coverage target, and confirm read yield and % reads identified upstream before concluding under-sequencing. Flag samples below the runbook's coverage target for a top-up/rerun decision, and report depth and breadth as distinct signals rather than one number.", "attach_to": "coverage", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "Low mean/median coverage often reflects low library yield, under-loading/under-sequencing, or fewer reads assigned after demux; because depth is modality-specific, the guard interprets it against the assay's configured target (from the runbook) instead of a universal number and proposes a top-up rather than a silent pass.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 2 — mean/median coverage (per-modality); runbook qc_thresholds", "tags": ["qc", "coverage"]}
{"id": "repair_low_reads_identified", "category": "qc", "rule_ids": ["QC-PCT_READS_IDENTIFIED"], "title": "Low % reads identified / low yield", "keywords": ["reads", "identified", "percent", "yield", "assigned", "demultiplex", "demux", "undetermined", "index", "pooling", "loading", "low"], "summary": "After demux, add an undetermined-index and pooling-balance check that inspects the undetermined-index report and the per-sample read share, and flags a low-yield sample for i7/i5 verification. When an index error is confirmed, prefer re-demultiplexing to recover reads over resequencing.", "attach_to": "demux", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "A low fraction of reads identified (a high undetermined fraction) often reflects index-read quality problems, sample-sheet index errors, or uneven pooling rather than a per-sample defect, so the guard checks the demux inputs first and can recover reads without a new sequencing run.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 1/2 — yield + % reads identified; runbook qc_thresholds", "tags": ["qc", "demux"]}
{"id": "repair_high_duplication", "category": "qc", "rule_ids": ["QC-DUP_RATE"], "title": "Elevated duplication rate", "keywords": ["duplication", "duplicate", "dup", "rate", "percent", "markdup", "picard", "complexity", "pcr", "optical", "amplicon", "input", "library"], "summary": "Confirm duplicate marking is enabled and correctly configured at the markdup stage, and interpret the duplication rate against the assay's expected band (amplicon high by design; hyb-capture/WES lower) from the runbook. Flag an unexpectedly high hyb/WES library for input-amount and PCR-cycle review, and report effective (deduplicated) coverage alongside the raw figure.", "attach_to": "markdup", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "Elevated duplication frequently indicates low library complexity, over-amplification, or optical duplicates, and expected duplication is assay-dependent — so the guard interprets it against the configured band rather than a universal cut and points at the wet-lab cause instead of altering the data.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 2 — Picard PERCENT_DUPLICATION (assay-tuned); runbook qc_thresholds", "tags": ["qc", "markdup"]}
{"id": "repair_low_cluster_pf", "category": "qc", "rule_ids": ["QC-CLUSTER_PF"], "title": "Low cluster PF (pass-filter)", "keywords": ["cluster", "pf", "passing", "filter", "loading", "overclustering", "density", "lane", "run", "low", "below"], "summary": "Treat cluster PF as a run/lane loading signal: add a lane-level PF check comparing against the runbook's configured PF gate, and route low-PF lanes to the sequencing team to review loading concentration and clustering rather than adjusting the analysis pipeline.", "attach_to": "read_qc", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "Cluster PF reflects flow-cell loading and clustering (over- or under-loading), which is a sequencing-side cause; the guard surfaces it at the lane level for a wet-lab decision and does not attempt a pipeline data fix. The gate value is read from the runbook.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 2 — cluster PF; runbook qc_thresholds", "tags": ["qc", "read_qc"]}
{"id": "repair_contamination_freemix", "category": "contamination", "rule_ids": [], "title": "Elevated cross-sample contamination estimate", "keywords": ["contamination", "freemix", "verifybamid", "verifybamid2", "cross", "sample", "mixture", "snp", "mixup", "identity", "estimate"], "summary": "Add a cross-sample contamination estimate (e.g. VerifyBamID2 FREEMIX) on the aligned BAM and gate it against the runbook's configured contamination band, escalating to a chain-of-custody review above the configured limit rather than releasing. Correlate any hit with the identity/swap check. This is an advisory guard; a human confirms before any action.", "attach_to": "align", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "An elevated FREEMIX suggests DNA from more than one individual (a sample mix-up, index hopping, or wet-lab cross-contamination); adding the estimate and gating on the runbook's band catches it before release. The band comes from the runbook — no threshold is asserted here — and this is a heuristic, not a diagnostic determination.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 2 — VerifyBamID2 FREEMIX (band per runbook); ADR-0008 issue taxonomy", "tags": ["qc", "contamination", "align"]}
{"id": "repair_sample_swap_identity", "category": "identity", "rule_ids": [], "title": "Sample identity / swap signal", "keywords": ["identity", "swap", "ngscheckmate", "concordance", "fingerprint", "genotype", "sex", "mismatch", "tumor", "normal", "pair", "pairing", "mislabel", "custody"], "summary": "Add an identity/fingerprint concordance check (e.g. NGSCheckMate) plus a declared-sex-vs-coverage cross-check on the aligned BAM, and fail closed on discordance, escalating as a chain-of-custody issue for human reconciliation against LIMS. Do not auto-repair a pairing; a human must confirm the swap.", "attach_to": "align", "scope": "qc", "rationale": "An identity/swap signal (fingerprint discordance, or a sex-vs-coverage disagreement) suggests a mislabel, a swap, or an incorrect tumor-normal pairing; the guard surfaces it and holds for reconciliation rather than making a determination, since resolving a swap is a human chain-of-custody decision.", "source": "docs/data/qc_metrics.md Gate 2 — NGSCheckMate identity/swap (ESCALATE); ADR-0008 issue taxonomy", "tags": ["qc", "identity", "align"]}
